articular, a 'constructional' approach that treats morphosyntactic constructions as meaningful in and of themselves. Thus, they are able to address the role of human cognitive embodiment in determining the meanings of linguistic phenomena as diverse as verbal affixes, discourse particles, prepositional phrases, lexical items, and tense semantics in both Greek and Latin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 3.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAncient history. 0aHistory, Ancient. 0aPhilology. Linguistics. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Historical & Comparative.2bisacsh  aGreek.  aLatin.  aclassical cognitive linguistics.  aembodied meaning.1 aAllan, Rutger J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonifazi, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrucale, Luisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDrummen, Annemieke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD'Anselmi, Luca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFedriani, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuraghi, Silvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMembrez, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMocciaro, Egle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPapadopoulou, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSausa, Eleonora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1